o the artwork, which is not only a principal source of the appeal of comic books but also central to the values these works embody. Brown argues that superheroes are to be taken not as representations of people but as iconic types, and the art conveys this. Even the most realistic comic illustrations are designed to suggest not persons but ideas—ideas about bodies and societies. Thus the appearance of superheroes both directly and indirectly influences the story being told as well as the opinions readers form concerning justice, authority, gender, puberty, sexuality, ethnicity, violence, and other concepts central to political and cultural life.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aComic books, strips, etcxIllustrationsxHistory and criticism. 0aComic books, strips, etcxIllustrationsxSocial aspects. 0aComic books, strips, etcxIllustrationsxThemes, motives. 0aComic books, strips, etc.xIllustrationsxHistory and criticism. 0aComic books, strips, etc.xIllustrationsxSocial aspects. 0aComic books, strips, etc.xIllustrationsxThemes, motives. 0aSuperheroes in comics. 0aSuperheroesvComic books, strips, etc. 0aSuperheroesxSocial aspects. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  aComics Industry, Graphic Narratives, Artistic Genres, Popular Literature, Jim Lee, Darwyn Cooke.  aJoe Shuster, Tim Sale, Humberto Ramos, Alex Ross, Alex Maleev, Andrea Sorrentino.  aSuperheroes, Comic Books, Art Styles, Illustration, Artists, Popular Culture.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Texas Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311079782440uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/32736440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781477327371423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781477327371/original  a978-3-11-079782-4  University of Texas Press Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  a